It's wet and cold, and sometimes you think the sun doesn't want to come at all.

256
00:15:39,602 --> 00:15:42,602
But now I have a warm scarf.

257
00:15:52,424 --> 00:15:57,984
The old woman may be very old, but her health is surprisingly good.

258
00:15:57,984 --> 00:16:00,224
I'm glad you think that, Mr. Heimerath.

259
00:16:00,224 --> 00:16:02,864
If I only knew how to decide.

260
00:16:02,864 --> 00:16:07,424
I am convinced that there is hardly anything better for Clara than the good air.

261
00:16:07,424 --> 00:16:13,064
Look at Heidi and then imagine what she looked like when she came back from
Frankfurt.

262
00:16:13,064 --> 00:16:16,264
Yes, I know, she was pale and slim, she was sick.

263
00:16:16,510 --> 00:16:19,310
I'm just afraid of the steep slopes.

264
00:16:19,510 --> 00:16:21,310
Tell me, I wanted to ask you that earlier.

265
00:16:21,510 --> 00:16:24,310
Do you really believe that Clara will ever be healthy again?

266
00:16:24,510 --> 00:16:29,310
Well, at the moment I can't answer your question with a yes or a no.

267
00:16:29,510 --> 00:16:30,310
What?

268
00:16:30,510 --> 00:16:34,310
Clara would have to do the prescribed walking exercises regularly.

269
00:16:34,510 --> 00:16:36,310
But she's not strong enough.

270
00:16:36,510 --> 00:16:39,310
That's why I'd like to send her.

271
00:16:39,816 --> 00:16:46,816
Star cuddling. If I had a star cuddling, I could wish that Clara would come and
then it would be fulfilled.

272
00:17:09,816 --> 00:17:11,336
Subtitles by Stephanie Geiges

273
00:17:11,336 --> 00:17:16,336
Today the view is even better than yesterday

274
00:17:19,752 --> 00:17:23,752
From now on, you have to pick the freshest herbs on the meadow, Swinley.

275
00:17:23,752 --> 00:17:25,752
Your milk must be especially good.

276
00:17:25,752 --> 00:17:29,752
We have to prove to the secret council that it is good for Clara to come here.

277
00:17:29,752 --> 00:17:31,752
Good morning, Haydn.

278
00:17:31,752 --> 00:17:33,752
But you got up early.

279
00:17:33,752 --> 00:17:35,752
Not early enough, I wanted to be the first.

280
00:17:35,752 --> 00:17:38,752
But you were even earlier than me, as you can see.

281
00:17:38,752 --> 00:17:40,752
Ah, fresh goat's milk.

282
00:17:40,752 --> 00:17:44,752
It's still warm, they don't get fresh milk in Frankfurt.

283
00:17:45,752 --> 00:17:48,752
Ah, it smells good.

284
00:17:49,752 --> 00:17:51,752
Yes.

285
00:17:55,208 --> 00:17:57,208
Drink it all!

286
00:17:59,208 --> 00:18:02,208
Delicious! Fresh, healthy milk!

287
00:18:02,208 --> 00:18:05,208
That was very nice of you, thank you!

288
00:18:05,208 --> 00:18:08,208
That's good, yes! That's even very good!

289
00:18:08,208 --> 00:18:12,208
If the milk is as healthy as she said, then she must also be healthy for Clara!

290
00:18:12,208 --> 00:18:13,208
Yes, of course!

291
00:18:13,208 --> 00:18:17,208
Clara could drink as much goat milk as she wants, she can do that, right?

292
00:18:18,208 --> 00:18:20,208
Heidi, now listen!

293
00:18:20,208 --> 00:18:23,208
Why? Why are you making such a face? What is it?

294
00:18:23,208 --> 00:18:23,892
Listen!

295
00:18:23,892 --> 00:18:26,892
We talked about Clara's wheelchair yesterday, didn't we?

296
00:18:26,892 --> 00:18:28,892
Yes, we did.

297
00:18:28,892 --> 00:18:31,892
You have often seen that I have pushed the wheelchair.

298
00:18:31,892 --> 00:18:36,892
Yes, in Frankfurt, on flat earth, on a stone floor or on carpet.

299
00:18:36,892 --> 00:18:37,892
And?

300
00:18:37,892 --> 00:18:39,892
Heidi, that's enough.

301
00:18:39,892 --> 00:18:42,892
You sit with your head through the wall again, that's nonsense.

302
00:18:42,892 --> 00:18:45,892
It's really too dangerous for Clara. I thought about it.

303
00:18:45,892 --> 00:18:47,892
Then I just want to go through the wall with my head.

304
00:18:47,892 --> 00:18:50,892
Believe me, I'll treat Clara with all my heart.

305
00:18:51,476 --> 00:18:55,476
Can't you really understand that you can't drive with a wheelchair up here?

306
00:18:56,276 --> 00:18:59,476
Well then, because what do you think would happen

307
00:18:59,476 --> 00:19:03,476
if your Clara can't hold her wheelchair on your steep meadows anymore?

308
00:19:03,476 --> 00:19:05,476
That? Yes.

309
00:19:06,476 --> 00:19:08,476
Did you see it?

310
00:19:08,476 --> 00:19:12,476
Wheelchair, wheelchair, you're always talking about this stupid wheelchair.

311
00:19:12,476 --> 00:19:14,476
None of you think of Clara.

312
00:19:15,092 --> 00:19:16,492
It's about Clara.

313
00:19:16,492 --> 00:19:17,812
Clara wouldn't be alone.

314
00:19:17,812 --> 00:19:19,652
Grandfather, Peter and I are here.

315
00:19:19,652 --> 00:19:21,252
We would all be careful.

316
00:19:21,252 --> 00:19:24,652
If we all help together, we can do it, right?

317
00:19:25,852 --> 00:19:27,772
But the secret ride is against it.

318
00:19:27,772 --> 00:19:29,412
No, no, no, he can't do that.

319
00:19:29,412 --> 00:19:30,772
That can't be.

320
00:19:30,772 --> 00:19:34,212
I want Clara to come visit me and she wants it too.

321
00:19:38,412 --> 00:19:39,932
Our wooden cube.

322
00:19:49,726 --> 00:19:51,726
Broke up.

323
00:19:54,726 --> 00:19:58,726
Heidi, come in, we're having breakfast.

324
00:20:04,062 --> 00:20:07,822
What does it matter if she can't sit in the wheelchair?

325
00:20:07,822 --> 00:20:10,822
Clara hates her wheelchair. What does it matter to her?

326
00:20:10,822 --> 00:20:13,302
Can she go wherever she wants with it?

327
00:20:13,302 --> 00:20:17,302
You don't care about what Clara thinks.

328
00:20:17,302 --> 00:20:21,302
You don't care if Clara is sad.

329
00:20:21,302 --> 00:20:24,302
It's definitely possible without this wheelchair.

330
00:20:24,302 --> 00:20:26,302
And even better than with it.

331
00:20:26,302 --> 00:20:28,302
Please, grandfather, please!

332
00:20:28,302 --> 00:20:31,302
Why shouldn't Clara sit in the grass on the meadow?

333
00:20:31,302 --> 00:20:32,564
She would like that.

334
00:20:32,564 --> 00:20:36,564
I know that. And she doesn't roll down the slope.

335
00:20:36,564 --> 00:20:40,564
But you don't want to let anything else come to mind.

336
00:20:40,564 --> 00:20:44,564
Clara would be happy here. She told me.

337
00:20:46,564 --> 00:20:48,564
Heidi.

338
00:20:50,564 --> 00:20:52,564
What the child says is right.

339
00:20:52,564 --> 00:20:56,564
We actually only thought about Clara's wheelchair all the time.

340
00:20:56,564 --> 00:21:00,564
I can carry her lightly and she can sit on the ground just as well.

341
00:21:00,564 --> 00:21:02,308
Wait a minute.

342
00:21:02,308 --> 00:21:08,808
Because I ... well, that could have been the problem the whole time.

343
00:21:08,808 --> 00:21:12,608
Clara has relied too much on her wheelchair.

344
00:21:12,608 --> 00:21:14,308
That is possible.

345
00:21:14,308 --> 00:21:18,108
We didn't make it clear to her once that it could go without this thing.

346
00:21:18,108 --> 00:21:21,808
Maybe she'll try to move when she's not sitting in this chair.

347
00:21:21,808 --> 00:21:23,408
Exactly.

348
00:21:23,408 --> 00:21:27,308
It's worth a try at least.

349
00:21:27,308 --> 00:21:28,808
Yes.

350
00:21:28,808 --> 00:21:31,608
One should ...

351
00:21:31,636 --> 00:21:33,636
I'll give it a try.

352
00:21:35,636 --> 00:21:37,636
I have to thank you.

353
00:21:37,636 --> 00:21:39,636
So?

354
00:21:39,636 --> 00:21:41,636
We'll do it.

355
00:21:41,636 --> 00:21:43,636
Why not? I don't know what I was against at all.

356
00:21:45,636 --> 00:21:47,636
Is that a promise or not?

357
00:21:47,636 --> 00:21:49,636
It is a promise.

358
00:21:49,636 --> 00:21:51,636
I promise you that she will come.

359
00:21:51,636 --> 00:21:53,636
And you promise me that you will take good care of her

360
00:21:53,636 --> 00:21:55,636
and that you won't let her out of your sight.

361
00:21:56,410 --> 00:21:59,910
There you can see what kind of an old donkey I am.

362
00:21:59,910 --> 00:22:01,910
A dear donkey.

363
00:22:03,910 --> 00:22:05,910
Clara, come on.

364
00:22:12,910 --> 00:22:17,410
That she can be so overbearing, I would never have thought that in Frankfurt.

365
00:22:17,410 --> 00:22:19,410
Here she is always like that.

366
00:22:22,910 --> 00:22:25,410
I have to tell him that right away.

367
00:22:26,410 --> 00:22:28,180
I have to tell him.

368
00:22:28,180 --> 00:22:31,180
Hurry up, Peter. I have news for you.

369
00:22:31,180 --> 00:22:34,180
For Heidi, the world was back in order.

370
00:22:34,180 --> 00:22:38,180
Finally, she would be able to show Clara all that she had always told her.

371
00:22:38,180 --> 00:22:40,180
The mountains, the ponds, the meadows.

372
00:22:40,180 --> 00:22:44,180
And, of course, Peter and the goat herd.

373
00:22:53,428 --> 00:23:00,428
Day after day, Heidi waited, after the secret council had left, impatiently for
a sign of life from Clara.

374
00:23:00,428 --> 00:23:04,428
She kept describing to Peter and his grandfather how Clara looked like.

375
00:23:04,428 --> 00:23:08,428
And then one day came the long-awaited letter from Frankfurt.

376
00:23:08,428 --> 00:23:10,428
Heidi was out of joy.

377
00:23:10,428 --> 00:23:18,428
And although she knew exactly that the secret council would keep its promise,
she could no longer grasp it at once.

378
00:23:19,428 --> 00:23:22,266
However, one thing Clara had not written.

379
00:23:22,266 --> 00:23:27,666
She had not dared, out of fear that Heidi might be disappointed or would even
give up.

380
00:23:27,666 --> 00:23:31,866
But we want to tell you about that in our next story.

381
00:23:31,866 --> 00:23:40,066
Heidi, Heidi, your world are the mountains.

382
00:23:40,066 --> 00:23:48,066
Heidi, Heidi, because up here you are at home.

383
00:23:48,066 --> 00:23:54,066
Heidi, Heidi, come home.

384
00:23:54,066 --> 00:24:01,066
Find your happiness, come back home.

